      <section class="prose" style="margin-top: 3rem;">
        <h2>What is Cryptographic Hashing?</h2>
        <p>
          Cryptographic hashing is a mathematical algorithm that maps data of arbitrary size to a bit string of a fixed size (a hash). This is designed to be a one-way function—meaning it is computationally infeasible to invert the hash and retrieve the original text. A <strong>hash generator online</strong> allows you to compute these digests instantly.
        </p>
        <h3>Hashing vs. Encryption</h3>
        <p>
          A common misconception is that hashing is a form of encryption. Encryption is a two-way function where data is scrambled using a key and can be decrypted later. Hashing is a one-way function. Once data is converted using a <strong>text to hash converter</strong>, it cannot be reversed. 
        </p>
        <h3>Common Algorithms</h3>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>MD5:</strong> Creates a 128-bit (32 character) hash. While an <strong>md5 hash generator</strong> is still useful for simple checksums to verify file integrity, MD5 is cryptographically broken and should <em>never</em> be used for password hashing or security applications.</li>
          <li><strong>SHA-1:</strong> Creates a 160-bit (40 character) hash. Like MD5, SHA-1 is now considered deprecated for cryptographic security due to vulnerability to collision attacks.</li>
          <li><strong>SHA-256:</strong> Creates a 256-bit (64 character) hash. This is the current industry standard. If you need a <strong>sha256 hash calculator</strong> for passwords (with a salt), blockchain applications (like Bitcoin), or SSL certificates, this is the algorithm to use.</li>
          <li><strong>SHA-512:</strong> Creates a 512-bit (128 character) hash. Provides maximum security and is often faster on 64-bit processors than SHA-256.</li>
        </ul>
        <h3>Use Cases</h3>
        <p>
          Hashes are fundamental to modern computer security. They are used for safely storing passwords in databases (so the plain text is never known), checking if a file has been corrupted during download (checksums), creating digital signatures, and securing blockchain ledgers. When you <strong>generate sha256 hash online free</strong> using our tool, your text is processed entirely in your browser via the Web Crypto API, ensuring your sensitive data is never sent to our servers.
        </p>
      </section>
    
